With the share name (profiles) identified, we proceed to the exploitation phase.

3. Vulnerability Analysis
🔴 SMB — Null Session / Anonymous Access
The SMB service was vulnerable to anonymous share access. This is a misconfiguration where the server allows the IPC$ share and other data shares to be queried without authentication. In production environments, this leaks user lists and file structures, providing attackers with an immediate foothold.
🔴 Telnet — Plaintext Protocol & Backdoor
Unlike SSH, Telnet does not encrypt traffic. Any credentials or commands sent are visible to anyone sniffing the network. Discovering Telnet on a non-standard port (8012) typically indicates a management backdoor or a poorly implemented service lacking modern security wrappers.
🔴 FTP — Information Disclosure via Anonymous Login
Allowing anonymous login (anonymous:anonymous) becomes a serious vulnerability when sensitive files like PUBLIC_NOTICE.txt are present. This file leaked the username mike, effectively reducing our attack surface from a full brute-force to a password-only attack.

