7. Remediation & Hardening
As a cybersecurity professional, the following remediations are required to properly secure this infrastructure:
SMB

Disable Null Session access in /etc/samba/smb.conf
Add restrict anonymous = 2 to prevent unauthenticated queries
Enable SMB Signing to prevent relay attacks
Regularly audit share permissions and remove guest access

Telnet

Decommission the Telnet service immediately — it has no legitimate use in modern infrastructure
Replace all Telnet usage with SSH to ensure end-to-end encryption
Audit non-standard ports via firewall rules and IDS policies

FTP

Disable anonymous access in vsftpd.conf: anonymous_enable=NO
Enforce a Strong Password Policy (minimum 12 characters with special symbols)
Migrate to SFTP or FTPS to encrypt file transfers
Never store sensitive user information in publicly accessible directories

Identity & Access Management

Never store SSH keys (.ssh/id_rsa) in network shares accessible by guest accounts
Implement an IAM framework to audit file access and enforce least privilege
Apply the Principle of Least Privilege across all shared resources


